The most likely cause is that you never set the page's **`BindingContext`** to your ViewModel. The `{Binding …}` markup works, but it has nothing to bind *against*.

**Fix — set the BindingContext** (pick one approach):

**Option A – Code-behind (constructor injection):**
```csharp
public partial class MyPage : ContentPage
{
    public MyPage(MyViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Option B – XAML-only:**
```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             ...>
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:MyViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>
    ...
</ContentPage>
```

**Also verify** that your ViewModel raises `PropertyChanged` when values are set after construction:

```csharp
public class MyViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    string _title;
    public string Title
    {
        get => _title;
        set { _title = value; OnPropertyChanged(); }
    }
    // ... same for Description

    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler PropertyChanged;
    void OnPropertyChanged([CallerMemberName] string n = null)
        => PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new PropertyChangedEventArgs(n));
}
```

> **Tip:** The MAUI Community Toolkit's `ObservableObject` base class (or `[ObservableProperty]` source generator) eliminates this boilerplate.
